 well need legislative authorization for such a thing. It isn't clear until we see which way we're going.\par \par \uc2 Powell's remarks come following his comments at the Senate Banking Committee yesterday, in which he said the Federal Reserve was carefully considering whether the United States should launch a digital dollar. The Fed Chair also said that it was unlikely for stablecoins and digital currencies to affect monetary policy transmission.\par \par \uc2 The Federal Reserve was also dealing with another technical challenge today, as the majority of its services provided through its online portal were inaccessible to the public for over an hour. At the time of writing, all Federal Reserve Bank Services with the exception of Account Services have resumed and are available online.\par \par \uc2 The approach to CBDC from the United States has been a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://blockchain.news/news/us-federal-reserve-weighs-pros-cons-digital-dollar-cbdc"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 huge contrast}}}\uc2  from the strategy adopted by China, who has been quick to introduce a pilot version of its digital currency electronic payment (DCEP).\par \par \uc2 With the growing popularity of cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin, central banks worldwide have reacted by experimenting with digital currencies of their own to remain financially relevant. In addition, the issuance of CBDCS by global economies may be an eventuality, as technological innovation is on the rise and the need for digital payments to be conducted efficiently, securely, and quickly is more important now than ever.\par \par \uc2 Document BLCRNW0020210226eh2q00003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw200\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal3000\pichgoal600
