\par\par \uc2 Altcoins\par \b \uc2 Bitcoin is 57,000 Times Less Environmentally Friendly Than the "Green Cryptocurrency" XRP, Says Ripple\b0\par\par\uc2 Sarah Tran \par \uc2 480 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 July 2020\par \uc2 Blockchain.News\par \uc2 BLCRNW\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2020. Worldmoney Blockchain Management Co., Limited \par \par \uc2 Ripple claims that its cryptocurrency, XRP, is 57,000 times more environmentally friendly than the largest cryptocurrency, Bitcoin.\par \par \uc2 According to Ripple's {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ripple.com/insights/the-environmental-impact-cryptocurrency-mining-vs-consensus/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2  blog post }}}\uc2  , the firm criticizes Bitcoin's consensus mechanism, proof-of-work (PoW), as a major issue contributing to the vast amounts of energy consumed for validating and processing transactions on the network. Other cryptocurrencies that use PoW as its consensus mechanism include \uc2 Litecoin\uc2 , Monero, Dash, Zcash, and Verge.\par \par \uc2 As users broadcast transactions to the network, miners who create the block which is then added to the network, uses some of their own resources, including computing power, which is used to hash the block's data until a solution to the cryptographic puzzle is found.\par \par \uc2 With the growing number of miners in the community, miners compete against each other to solve the puzzle and verify the block, which then earns them a reward is to use more computational power to solve the puzzle quickly.\par \par \uc2 Ripple's post, written by Ripple's CTO David Schwartz mentioned that with an application-specific device, ASIC miner, has an \uc2 environmental\uc2  cost of $1,500 per year for mining, while newer versions of mining machines could cost as much as $6,000 per year.\par \par \uc2 A study conducted in 2018 found that the hundreds of thousands of computers that were used to solve cryptographic puzzles working 24 hours a day to mine Bitcoin consumed 1.5 times the yearly energy consumption of Ireland.\par \par \uc2 Ripple says XRP is a green cryptocurrency\par \par \uc2 According to Ripple's blog post, XRP was designed with \uc2 sustainability\uc2  in mind, and claims the cryptocurrency to be inherently green. Unlike Bitcoin, where there is a maximum supply to be mined, all XRP is already in existence, meaning no additional mining processes that require energy consumption will be needed to produce more.\par \par \uc2 The unsustainable mining practices and proof-of-work mechanism behind Bitcoin and Ethereum are massive barriers for the more widespread adoption of cryptocurrencies. But not all blockchains are made equally.\par \par \uc2 Ripple compared the energy consumption between 1 million transactions of XRP and Bitcoin. 1 million transactions in XRP could power 79,000 lightbulb hours, and 1 million transactions in Bitcoin could power 4.51 billion lightbulb hours, meaning XRP is 57,000 times more efficient than Bitcoin, according to the post.\par \par \uc2 Blockchain and \uc2 sustainability\par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2 , the consumer goods company that owns brands such as Ben Jerry's, Dove, Vaseline, Knorr, and other well-known brands, has {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://blockchain.news/news/unilever-blockchain-transparency-traceability-deforestation-supply-chain"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2  announced }}}\uc2  that it will be leveraging blockchain to tackle deforestation.\par \par \uc2 By introducing transparency and traceability into its supply chain process, \uc2 Unilever\uc2  hopes to achieve a deforestation-free supply chain by 2023. The consumer goods company is also introducing a new regenerative agriculture code for its suppliers, and stewardship programs for local communities in the next few years.\par \par \uc2 Document BLCRNW0020200709eg790002t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
