\par\par \uc2 Enterprise\par \b \uc2 Unilever\uc2  to Use Blockchain for Transparency and Traceability to Achieve Deforestation-Free Supply Chain by 2023\b0\par\par\uc2 Sarah Tran \par \uc2 416 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 June 2020\par \uc2 Blockchain.News\par \uc2 BLCRNW\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2020. Worldmoney Blockchain Management Co., Limited \par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2 , the consumer goods company that owns brands such as Ben Jerry s, Dove, Vaseline, Knorr, and other well-known brands, has announced that it will be leveraging blockchain to tackle deforestation.\par \par \uc2 The British-Dutch multinational consumer goods company has set out a new range of measures to improve the health of the planet and to fight \uc2 climate change\uc2 , and global warming. \uc2 Unilever\uc2  aims to achieve Net Zero emissions from all of its products by 2039.\par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2  s brands will collectively invest 1 billion euros in a new Climate and Nature Fund, to fund projects including landscape restoration, reforestation, carbon sequestration, wildlife protection, and water preservation.\par \par \uc2 Around 30 percent of the world s landmass is covered by forests, and sections of forests around half the size of England are lost every year due to deforestation. Rainforests act as the planet s lungs, by absorbing carbon dioxide and supplying the air with oxygen in return. Deforestation sends a major influx of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere which fuels \uc2 climate change\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In most parts of the world, the economic and social inclusion of farmers and smallholders in sustainable agricultural production is the single most important driver of change for halting deforestation, restoring forests, and helping regenerate nature, said Marc Engel, Chief Supply Chain Officer at Unilever.\par \par \uc2 By introducing transparency and traceability into its supply chain process, \uc2 Unilever\uc2  hopes to achieve a deforestation-free supply chain by 2023. The consumer goods company is also introducing a new regenerative agriculture code for its suppliers, and stewardship programs for local communities in the next few years.\par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2  previously integrated blockchain technology for its business to restructure the way demographic and location data are collected, saved, and verified.\par \par \uc2 The company is also committed to working with non-governmental organizations (NGOs), and governments to protect other important areas of high conservation value. \uc2 Unilever\uc2  is also looking to help regenerate nature, by increasing local biodiversity, restoring soil health, and preserving water conservation and access. We will empower a new generation of farmers and smallholders who are committed to protecting and regenerating their farm environment.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Economic Forum\uc2  (WEF) has also committed to empowering organizations of any size to leverage blockchain technology to tackle supply chain issues, highlighted by the coronavirus pandemic. Blockchain.News interviewed Nadia Hewett , the Blockchain Lead at the Forum, who explained the current use-cases of the toolkit launched by the organization.\par \par \uc2 Document BLCRNW0020200616eg6g0002t\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw300\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4500\pichgoal600
